karn@servo.qualcomm.com (Phil Karn) writes:
> The computer industry has discovered a far more effective and 
> realistic way to set standards.  First you produce an experimental 
> product and get it out into the market. Then you revise it as needed to 
> meet actual customer needs. Once it has stablized and is in 
> widespread use, only THEN do you codify it as an "official standard". 
> 
> What a novel concept. 

Indeed.  Since PGP has not stabilized or found widespread use in the Internet 
community, I figured he was trying to assert a standard de jure rather than 
de facto, and noted that I have seen no evidence of such activity.

PGP is no more a "worldwide standard" than Fidonet is.



